artin</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Lewis</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=PP%2FC001214%2F1"><gtr:id>C944A0BC-DE7F-4596-8768-30D32474B020</gtr:id><gtr:title>Cosmology from the Cosmic Microwave Background</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>PP/C001214/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The Big Bang model describes a universe that was initially very hot and dense and has expanded steadily to its current state. It has met with considerable observational success. However many important questions remain unanswered about the physics of the early universe: how did 'inflation' of the universe happen? What was before or how did it start? What was the underlying theory? We also currently do not know what makes up most of the mass and energy in the universe, or what the future holds for us! Fortunately we are at an observational turning point, with a host of experiments planned and under way that should help to answer some of these basic questions. It is therefore an immensely exciting time to working in cosmology. For the first time in human history we have the possibility of using detailed data to assess, reject, or hone our theoretical models. The cosmic microwave background (CMB) radiation fills the universe, and by observing it we can see back to when the universe was just a few hundred thousand years old. Tiny perturbations that we can see in the distribution of the radiation tell us about what matter distribution of the universe looked like when the universe was 1000 times smaller. These 'CMB anisotropies' can be modelled accurately theoretically, allowing us to trace back the perturbations to times close to the big bang. Many current theories suggest that there was an exponential expansion of the universe at very early times, so called 'inflation'. Small fluctuations generated during this period get blown up to huge scales that we may be observing in the CMB. Observation of the CMB anisotropies therefore potentially tell us about the primordial fluctuations that grew to form the universe we see today, as well as how the universe evolved at very early times. Details of this process may lead us to confirm or reject models of fundamental physics at energy scales far out of reach of laboratory accelerators. Of course there are many hurdles to overcome to make robust inferences about cosmology from observations. The theoretical modelling needs to be ever more accurate, and I plan to extend and develop current methods to keep pace with the improving observations. There are also numerous problems to be tackled to turn observations of the CMB today into clean maps of the primordial universe. For example foregrounds, gravitational lensing and the unknown more recent evolution of the universe can complicate the analysis, as well as being things we're interested to study in their own right. I anticipate participating in active research projects in Cambridge dealing with these challenges, particularly with the Planck satellite observations planned for 2007. Ultimately I'm interested in the underlying physics of the universe, and what we can learn about fundamental physics. As the field evolves from being data-starved but flooded with untested theories, to having detailed data available and tight constraints, I hope to work on the theoretical models compatible with the observations. Fundamental questions about the origin and nature of the universe are of interest to almost everyone, and I hope to help provide answers to at least some of the questions.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/D7F4F462-0518-4784-908A-D12633C139B3"><gtr:id>D7F4F462-0518-4784-908A-D12633C139B3</gtr:id><gtr:name>STFC</